  <section>
    <h2>üöÄ Initial Setup: Creating a Child Account</h2>

    <h3>On Parent's Device</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Install Family Link for Parents</strong>
        <p>Download "Google Family Link for parents" from the Google Play Store (Android) or App Store (iOS).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Open the app and sign in</strong>
        <p>Use your existing Google account (the one you want to use as the parent/manager account).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tap "Get started"</strong>
        <p>Choose "Yes" when asked if your child has a Google Account. If they don't, you'll create one.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Create child's Google Account</strong>
        <p>Enter your child's name, birthday, and gender. For children under 13 (or applicable age in your country), Family Link is required by law.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Create child's Gmail address</strong>
        <p>Choose an email address like <code>firstname.lastname@gmail.com</code> or let Google suggest one. Write this down!</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Create a secure password</strong>
        <p>Create a strong password for your child's account. Store this securely‚Äîyou'll need it to sign in to their device.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Agree to Google's Family Link disclosure</strong>
        <p>Review the information about data collection and parental controls. You must give parental consent.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Choose parental controls settings</strong>
        <p>The app will walk you through initial settings. You can customize these more later.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-warning">
      <strong>Important:</strong> Write down the child's email address and password before continuing! You'll need these to set up their device.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üì± Setting Up the Child's Device</h2>

    <h3>Option 1: New Device or Factory Reset (Easiest)</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Power on the device</strong>
        <p>If it's a used device, perform a factory reset first (Settings ‚Üí System ‚Üí Reset options ‚Üí Erase all data).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Follow the setup wizard</strong>
        <p>Choose language, connect to WiFi, etc.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Sign in with child's Google account</strong>
        <p>When prompted to add a Google account, enter the email and password you created.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>When prompted, enter parent code</strong>
        <p>The device will display a code. Enter this code in the Family Link app on your device to link them.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Choose device name</strong>
        <p>Give the device a recognizable name (e.g., "Emma's Phone").</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Select apps to install</strong>
        <p>Choose which apps to install on the child's device. Family Link will show recommended apps.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Finish setup</strong>
        <p>Complete the remaining setup steps. The device is now supervised!</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Option 2: Existing Device with Data</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Install Family Link for Children</strong>
        <p>On the child's device, download "Google Family Link for children" from Play Store.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Open the app and tap "Get Started"</strong>
        <p>Follow the prompts to connect to parent's account.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Enter child's Google Account credentials</strong>
        <p>Sign in with the account you created earlier.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Link to parent account</strong>
        <p>Follow the prompts to connect. You may need to enter a code from the parent app.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Grant permissions</strong>
        <p>The child device will need to grant various permissions for supervision to work.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-warning">
      <strong>Note:</strong> On existing devices, some data may need to be backed up and removed. A factory reset with Option 1 is cleaner and more reliable.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üîê Essential Controls to Configure</h2>

    <h3>App Management</h3>
    <p>Control what apps your child can use:</p>

    <h4>Approving and Blocking Apps</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>In Family Link app, tap your child's name</li>
      <li>Go to "Controls" ‚Üí "Apps & activities"</li>
      <li>View all installed apps and their permissions</li>
      <li>Toggle apps on or off to allow or block them</li>
      <li>Set "App install approval" to require your permission</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-info">
      <strong>Recommended:</strong> Enable "App install approval" so your child must request permission to download new apps. This provides teachable moments and prevents inappropriate downloads.
    </div>

    <h4>Age-Appropriate Content</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to "Google Play" settings in Family Link</li>
      <li>Set content restrictions:
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Apps & Games:</strong> Choose rating (Everyone, Everyone 10+, Teen, Mature 17+)</li>
          <li><strong>Movies:</strong> Set maximum rating (G, PG, PG-13, etc.)</li>
          <li><strong>TV:</strong> Set maximum TV rating</li>
          <li><strong>Books:</strong> Show or hide books with mature content</li>
          <li><strong>Music:</strong> Block explicit content</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Require authentication for purchases</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Chrome & Web Filtering</h3>
    <p>Control web browsing and search results:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to "Filters on Google Chrome"</li>
      <li>Choose filtering level:
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Try to block mature sites:</strong> Automatic filtering (recommended for most children)</li>
          <li><strong>Only allow certain sites:</strong> Whitelist mode (most restrictive, best for young children)</li>
          <li><strong>Allow all sites:</strong> No filtering (only for older teens)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Manage exceptions: Add sites to always allow or block</li>
      <li>Enable "SafeSearch" to filter explicit results in Google Search</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-warning">
      <strong>Limitation:</strong> Chrome filtering only works in the Chrome browser. Consider disabling other browsers or using device-wide DNS filtering for additional protection.
    </div>

    <h3>Google Search Settings</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to "Google Search" in Family Link</li>
      <li>Turn on "SafeSearch" to filter explicit content</li>
      <li>This applies to Google Search, Google Images, and YouTube</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Screen Time & App Limits</h3>

    <h4>Daily Screen Time Limit</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>Tap "Daily limit" in Family Link</li>
      <li>Set maximum screen time per day (e.g., 3 hours)</li>
      <li>Choose whether to apply the same limit every day or customize by day of week</li>
      <li>When the limit is reached, the device locks except for parent-approved apps</li>
    </ol>

    <h4>Bedtime</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>Tap "Bedtime" in Family Link</li>
      <li>Set device lock times (e.g., 8:30 PM to 7:00 AM)</li>
      <li>Customize schedule for different days</li>
      <li>During bedtime, only calls to parent-approved contacts work</li>
    </ol>

    <h4>App Time Limits (Android 10+)</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to "App limits" in Family Link</li>
      <li>Set individual time limits for specific apps</li>
      <li>For example: TikTok 1 hour/day, YouTube 30 minutes/day</li>
      <li>Child can see how much time they have left</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-info">
      <strong>Bonus for Older Devices:</strong> If app limits aren't available, use "Daily limit" combined with blocking apps during certain times for similar control.
    </div>

    <h3>Location Tracking</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Ensure location services are enabled on child's device</li>
      <li>In Family Link, tap "Location" to see child's device location on a map</li>
      <li>View location history and set up location alerts (if available)</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-info">
      <strong>Privacy Consideration:</strong> Discuss location tracking with your child. Explain it's for safety, not surveillance. Respect their privacy as they mature.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üì∫ YouTube & YouTube Kids</h2>
    <p>
      YouTube content needs special attention for children:
    </p>

    <h3>For Younger Children (Under 10)</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Uninstall or block regular YouTube app</li>
      <li>Install <strong>YouTube Kids</strong> instead</li>
      <li>In Family Link, configure YouTube Kids:
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Preschool:</strong> Ages 4 and under</li>
          <li><strong>Younger:</strong> Ages 5-8</li>
          <li><strong>Older:</strong> Ages 9-12</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Approve content mode: Choose between curated collections or approved content only</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>For Older Children (10-12)</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>In Family Link, go to "YouTube" settings</li>
      <li>Choose supervised YouTube experience level:
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Explore:</strong> Broader range of videos, excludes mature content</li>
          <li><strong>Explore More:</strong> Larger selection, still restricted</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Search and comment features are limited</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>For Teens (13+)</h3>
    <p>
      At 13, children can choose to graduate from supervision to a regular Google Account. If they remain supervised:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Enable "Restricted Mode" in YouTube</li>
      <li>Consider allowing regular YouTube with monitoring</li>
      <li>Have conversations about responsible viewing</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-warning">
      <strong>YouTube Caution:</strong> Even with restrictions, YouTube's recommendation algorithm can surface inappropriate content. Regular monitoring and conversations are essential. Consider using dedicated guides: <a href="/guides/youtube-filtering">YouTube Filtering Guide</a>.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üìä Monitoring Activity</h2>

    <h3>Activity Reports</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Open Family Link and tap your child's name</li>
      <li>Tap "Activity" to view:
        <ul>
          <li>Total screen time today and weekly average</li>
          <li>Most used apps with time spent</li>
          <li>App activity breakdown by day</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Set up weekly activity email summaries (Settings ‚Üí Notifications)</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Managing the Device Remotely</h3>
    <p>From the Family Link app, you can:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Lock device:</strong> Instantly lock your child's device remotely</li>
      <li><strong>Play sound:</strong> Make device ring to help find it</li>
      <li><strong>See location:</strong> View current device location</li>
      <li><strong>Adjust controls:</strong> Change any setting without physical access</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

